body:
Here is one example.

```verilog
module top;

parameter WIDTH=256;

wire [5-1:0] ex1;
wire [5-1:0] ex2;
wire [5-1:0] ex3;

reg clk=0;

wire [WIDTH-1:0] out_data [2:0];

sub #(.RPORT(3), .WPORT(2), .WIDTH(256)) u0( 
    .clk(clk),
    .r_idx({ex1, ex2, ex3}),
    .r_dat(out_data)
);



endmodule


module sub(clk, r_idx, r_dat);

parameter RPORT = 3;
parameter WPORT = 2;
parameter WIDTH = 256;


input clk;
input [5-1:0] r_idx [RPORT-1:0];
output reg [WIDTH-1:0] r_dat[RPORT-1:0];

always @(posedge clk) begin
    r_dat[0] = {16{r_idx[0]}};
    r_dat[1] = {16{r_idx[1]}};
    r_dat[2] = {16{r_idx[2]}};
end

endmodule

```

The input r_idx in module sub is one 2-D array.
But one 1-D array is passed to it when sub is instantiated in module top.

To fix the issue in least cost, we could pass `{ex1, ex2, ex3} to port r_idx.

I tried VCS and Xcelium. Both of them do auto conversion (no compile warning).
Hope verilator can be enhanced to support it as well.
